prompt:

Create a FieldOps Fulfillment & Community platform that unifies on-site staff check-ins, local order delivery or pickup, and post-service trust building for multi-location operations that may run without internet. Users include Frontline Staff who perform one-tap check-ins and complete delivery/pickup tasks, Customers who place local orders and open after-sales tickets, Community Members who create posts and engage with others, Site Managers who oversee a single location’s performance and disputes, and System Administrators who configure rules and audit activity. The Angular web UI presents a role-based home dashboard with clear status chips (On Time, Late, Flagged) and immediate feedback for actions like check-in success, duplicate detection, or retry prompts. Check-in is designed as a single button that captures timestamp, approximate location as entered or selected from a preloaded site list (no online maps), and device fingerprint, then shows a confirmation screen with the captured evidence. Engagement features include upvote/downvote, favorites, and following authors/topics, plus a visible points meter with levels and badges (for example, +5 points for a new post, +1 for receiving an upvote, -10 for a removed post, level-ups at 100/300/700 points). Commerce flows support configuring local delivery, courier handoff, or in-store pickup, with address book management and delivery zones defined by ZIP code lists and distance bands (e.g., 0–5 miles $4.99, 5–10 miles $7.99) and printable shipping labels from the local printer. Store pickup uses an on-receipt 6-digit verification code that the staff enters at handoff; the UI records a redemption log and blocks reuse. After completion, both sides submit two-way ratings with 1–5 scores across timeliness, communication, and accuracy plus optional text; users can appeal within 7 days, triggering an arbitration workflow and a visible credit score impact explanation.

The backend uses Spring Boot to enforce business rules, validate requests, and persist data in PostgreSQL with an offline-first deployment that runs entirely on a local network or a single machine. Authentication is strictly local username/password with password rules of at least 10 characters including one number and one symbol; sessions expire after 30 minutes of inactivity, and privileged actions require re-entering the password within the last 10 minutes. Multi-role permissions support organization hierarchies (enterprise → site → team) and data scope down to site, device, and work order; every write action stores an immutable audit trail (who, when, device fingerprint, before/after) and supports manager review. Check-in validation rejects attempts outside an allowed window (e.g., 15 minutes before to 10 minutes after shift start), blocks duplicates within 60 minutes, and flags anomalies such as rapid repeated attempts (more than 5 in 10 minutes) or mismatched device binding; flagged records remain saved with raw evidence and a required supervisor note for resolution. The incentive engine is configurable in an admin console and runs server-side with anti-fraud heuristics that quarantine suspicious like rings (for example, more than 20 votes between the same two accounts in 24 hours) pending review. After-sales tickets support refund-only and return-and-refund paths with rule-based eligibility (return request within 14 days, auto-approve under $25.00 if no prior abuse, otherwise route to an agent), SLA timers (first response within 8 business hours), and dispute retention for 24 months; proof uploads are stored locally with format and size checks (PDF/JPG/PNG up to 10 MB) and content hashing for tamper detection. A local analytics module records standardized events, computes funnels and retention on-device, and powers dashboards for CTR, conversion, diversity, and satisfaction; experiments support A/B and bandit allocation with deterministic bucketing, feature backtracking, and version tracking for recommendation configurations, all exposed via RESTful APIs that the Angular frontend calls over the local network without any external dependencies. Sensitive fields (addresses, device identifiers, credit history) are encrypted at rest, and screens mask data by role to minimize unnecessary exposure.

project_type: fullstack
frontend_language: HTML/CSS/JS
backend_language: Java
frontend_framework: AngularJs
backend_framework: Spring Boot
database: PostgreSQL